    "helpContent": "In standard Mill, the goal is to reduce your opponent to fewer than three pieces or leave them with no legal move.\n\nThe game has up to three phases:\n\n1. Placing pieces on empty points\n2. Moving pieces to adjacent points\n3. Flying to any empty point when this optional rule is active\n\nPlacing\n\nThe standard board has 24 points. Players take turns placing one piece on an empty point until all pieces have been placed. Aligning three of your pieces along a marked line forms a mill and lets you remove one opposing piece. A piece in a mill can normally be removed only when the opponent has no other removable pieces.\n\nSome rule sets also prevent a piece from being placed again on a point where a piece was removed.\n\nMoving\n\nAfter all pieces have been placed, players take turns moving one piece along a board line to an adjacent empty point. Forming a mill allows another removal under the same rules as in the placing phase.\n\nFlying\n\nWhen flying is enabled and a player reaches the configured piece threshold, each of their pieces may move to any empty point instead of only to an adjacent point.\n\nWinning and draws\n\nA player normally loses after falling below three pieces or when they have no legal move. Depending on the selected rule set, a draw can result from repetition, agreement, a full board, or reaching a configured move limit without a removal. Custom rules may change these conditions.\n",
